  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation select (icmp eq
%a, %b), %a, %b -> %b is being applied and verified by InstSimplify, but Alive2
demonstrates it is incorrect in the presence of pointer provenance/liveness
differences. Even if the icmp eq evaluates true (equal address), selecting
between %a and %b can produce distinct pointer provenance, so blindly
substituting and choosing one arm is not semantics-preserving under a stronger
memory model.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe instsimplify pass is the first to
modify IR, replacing the select with the false arm (ret %b). This corresponds to
logic in InstructionSimplify's simplifySelectWithICmpCond and
simplifySelectWithEquivalence, which attempts to use equality to substitute
operands in select arms and if both arms simplify to the same value, returns the
false arm.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe function simplifySelectWithICmpCond
applies equivalence-based simplification for any ICmp eq, including pointer
equality. Specifically, for Pred == ICMP_EQ, it calls
simplifySelectWithEquivalence({{CmpLHS, CmpRHS}}, TrueVal, FalseVal,...). In the
reproducer, Cond is icmp eq ptr %a, %b; TrueVal is %a; FalseVal is %b.
Substituting %a->%b causes both arms to simplify to %b, and the code returns
FalseVal (%b). This is unsound for pointers due to provenance: choosing the other
operand may change the pointer identity/provenance even if addresses are equal.
The documentation comment above simplifySelectWithEquivalence says it is intended
for integer equality or floating-point equivalence. However, the current code
path incorrectly uses it for pointer equality, because m_ICmp matches pointer
compares too.\n\nTherefore, we need to restrict the equivalence-based select
simplification to integer (and FP in the separate FCmp path) but not pointer icmp
eq.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe will modify
llvm/lib/Analysis/InstructionSimplify.cpp within simplifySelectWithICmpCond to
guard the equivalence-based substitution under ICMP_EQ to only apply when the
comparison operands are of integer type. Concretely, before calling
simplifySelectWithEquivalence for ICMP_EQ, add a check to ensure
CmpLHS->getType()->isIntOrIntVectorTy(). If the type is pointer (or non-integer),
skip the equivalence substitution block.\n\nEdit at
llvm/lib/Analysis/InstructionSimplify.cpp lines ~4730-4760:\n- Insert a type
check guarding the ICMP_EQ equivalence simplification:\n\nif (Pred ==
ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ) {\n  // Only perform equivalence-based substitution for
integer compares.\n  Type *CmpTy = CmpLHS->getType();\n  if
(CmpTy->isIntOrIntVectorTy()) {\n    if (Value *V =
simplifySelectWithEquivalence({{CmpLHS, CmpRHS}}, TrueVal,\n
FalseVal, Q, MaxRecurse))\n      return V;\n    if (Value *V =
simplifySelectWithEquivalence({{CmpRHS, CmpLHS}}, TrueVal,\n
FalseVal, Q, MaxRecurse))\n      return V;\n\n    // ... keep existing
integer-specific patterns (|(X|Y)==0), (&(X&Y)==-1) ...\n    Value *X;\n    Value
*Y;\n    if (match(CmpLHS, m_Or(m_Value(X), m_Value(Y))) &&\n
match(CmpRHS, m_Zero())) {\n      if (Value *V = simplifySelectWithEquivalence(\n
{{X, CmpRHS}, {Y, CmpRHS}}, TrueVal, FalseVal, Q, MaxRecurse))\n        return
V;\n    }\n    if (match(CmpLHS, m_And(m_Value(X), m_Value(Y))) &&\n
match(CmpRHS, m_AllOnes())) {\n      if (Value *V =
simplifySelectWithEquivalence(\n              {{X, CmpRHS}, {Y, CmpRHS}},
TrueVal, FalseVal, Q, MaxRecurse))\n        return V;\n    }\n  }\n}\n\n- This
ensures the equivalence-based substitution is not applied to pointer equality
conditions, avoiding the unsound select folding demonstrated by Alive2.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nBy restricting simplifySelectWithEquivalence to integer equality
within simplifySelectWithICmpCond, we prevent incorrect simplification of selects
conditioned on pointer equality. The fix preserves intended behavior for integer
and floating-point cases while avoiding provenance-breaking transforms for
pointers. This should stop the erroneous replacement of select (icmp eq ptr %a,
%b), %a, %b with %b and restore correctness under stricter memory/provenance
models.",
